8:02 Fun facts ☺: These creatures are called Tanuki and they have been and still are very popular within Japanese folklore and culture in general. They are masters of disguise, incredibly mischievous and are said to live a very hedonist lifestyle. One of the most prominent characteristics of this creature is the very visible scrotum (exactly what you see in the video), which symbolises fertility, prosperity and luck. This is the reason why ceramic statues of tanuki with a straw hat and a sake jug can be found in front of a lot of restaurants, bars, and sake shops in Japan.

Hi Pewds! As a Scottish parent who raised a child in Japan I have some tips for raising Bjorn.

Bjorn is western, he will look different to Japanese kids, I recommend putting him in a western school to be educated because he won't be bullied and he will be able to make friends better. Teach him Swedish, Italian and Japanese, my son is fluent in English and is advanced at Japanese. This will help him so he can choose where he wants to live in the future. He will be able to socialise like you and Marzia have so you will flow better as a family. My Child was bullied his whole way through school and he wasn't like us socially because he was different so we took him out of the japanese schools at age 10. He went to an international school for 3 years until we moved back home and he loved the international school and his confidence and social skills grew a lot. We also got in contact with other British people who lived near Tokyo and he made lifelong friends that moved back last year and the year before.

Japanese food is very chemically treated. You should make sure that you buy organic food and if it is meat make sure it is higher welfare or grass fed because our families health improved once we did this.

Put your son into at least 3 sports to begin with. He will develop physical ability quickly and mature better. He will learn to socialise with Japanese kids as well but in a better environment than a school. I really regret not doing this with my son because I wanted to protect him when he was young but I was wrong. Kids don't get hurt that easily and I was too overprotective. He plays four sports now but if I started him when he was young he would've been able to play at a higher level which I regret.
